This does pass 86/102 test cases so I hope it's at least passable for an interview.

I wonder if it would fare better if I didn't make as heavy use of strings.

```
class Solution {

    int[] nums1;
    int[] nums2;

    public int[] maxNumber(int[] nums1, int[] nums2, int k) {
        this.nums1 = nums1;
        this.nums2 = nums2;
        Map<String, StringBuilder> memo = new HashMap<>();
        StringBuilder sb = helper(0, 0, k, memo);
        int[] output = new int[k];
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            output[i] = sb.charAt(i) - '0';
        }
        return output;
    }

    private String getKey(int i, int j, int k) {
        return i + "_" + j + "_" + k;
    }

    private StringBuilder helper(int i, int j, int k, Map<String, StringBuilder> memo) {
        if (k == 0) {
            return new StringBuilder();
        }
        String key = getKey(i, j, k);
        if (memo.containsKey(key)) {
            return memo.get(key);
        }
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        int nLeft = nums1.length - i + nums2.length - j;
        // Take digit
        if (i >= nums1.length) {
