solutions.content:
Taking the help of Hint provided, we can think to generate all possible paths to reach target (one digit changes by +1 pr -1 , as we can go clockwise or anti-clockwise , at each step) and return the shortest path.

**Algorithm may follow as below :**
Move forward if possible and increment the size of path by 1.
Else return
if we reached target value, return
Get the min of paths uptil now. and return this min value

**Code can be as follow:**  *(read comments to understand code)*

```
class Solution {
public:
    set<string> dead;
    int dfs(string start, string target, set<string>& visit){  //dfs function
        visit.insert(start); //marking it as visited
        if(dead.find(start) != dead.end())  // dead end is reach, so return infinite value
			return INT_MAX;
        if(start==target) { //target reached, return 0
            // cout<<"start="<<start<<","<<"path="<<0<<"\n";
            return 0;   
        }

        int path = INT_MAX; //infinite default value, as we need to use min function
        string temp = start; //copy of string created
        for(int i =0; i<start.length(); i++)
		{
             int k = temp[i]-'0'; 
             temp[i] = ((k+1)%10)+'0';      // +1 : clockwise movement
             if(visit.find(temp)==visit.end() && visit.find(target)==visit.end())
                 path = min (path, dfs(temp, target, visit));

             temp[i] = ((k-1+10)%10)+'0';    // -1 : anti-clockwise movement
             if(visit.find(temp)==visit.end() && visit.find(target)==visit.end())
				 path = min (path , dfs(temp, target, visit)); 
        }
        // visit.erase(visit.find(start)); // use it for backtracking solution
        if(path ==INT_MAX) return INT_MAX;
        // cout<<"start="<<start<<","<<"path="<<path<<"\n";
        return path+1;   
    }

    int openLock(vector<string>& deadends, string target) {
        for(string d : deadends)
            dead.insert(d);

        string start="0000"; //starting value
        set<string> visit;
        int ans = dfs(start, target, visit); // start dfs
        if(ans == INT_MAX) return -1;
        return ans;
    }
};
```

All looks good and should work. Right?
No
Why?
Cause we are using a visited set/array and doing dfs. This will create a grave problem by marking those nodes as visited which are common in both shortest path and non-shortest path. If we happen to traverse a non-shortest path before, its nodes will be marked visited and we get some path length , say **P'** . Now when we need to traverse a differnet path (may be the shortest path this time), it will not traverse those nodes , which are already traversed (marked visited). Hence we will never be able to know the value of shortest path length, say **P** . **(P  < P')**

Therefore DFS will not work.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2950c164-e79b-4b35-a3fa-7d3474acab76_1622908859.296736.png)




You must be thinking , ok, can we mark those node as un-visited after we have traversed a path. 
Sure, **this method is called BACKTRACKING**; where we reverse what was done.
Backtracking could solve the problem, but remember, this is not a tree, so you might end up re-traverseing the common node; For Example: in above figure, path after node **M** will we re-traversed in purple path although we have traversed it in path black, and can cause TLE

So the best method, to solve it is using BFS. As it will not mark any node visited before the shortest path reached its destination.

Happy coding! 
:)

