solutions.content:
By framing this problem as finding the shortest path in a graph of lock combinations, we can use Djikstra's algorithm. 

The traditional algorithm calculates path lengths in a breadth-first-search and needs to check if the current calculated path length to a node is less than that from another path and overwrite if necessary. However, since all step distances are the same here (1 turn of the lock number) we can make use of a number of shortcuts:

1. The first path length calculated for each node in the bfs will already be the shortest, so if we encounter it again we can skip it altogether.
2. We can make this a greedy algorithm and return the path length as soon as the target node is reached.

```
class Solution {
    public int openLock(String[] deadends, String target) {
        int[] v = new int[10000];
        for (String p : deadends) v[Integer.parseInt(p)] = -1;
        if (v[0] == -1) return -1; // optional, there were some examples where start was a deadend
		int tar = Integer.parseInt(target);
		Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        q.add(0);
        while (!q.isEmpty()) {
            int t = q.poll();
            if (t == tar) return v[tar]; // 2. greedy return
            int nextLen = v[t] + 1;
            for (int c = 1; c <= 1000; c *= 10) { // loop to +/- on all 4 coordinates
                int a = (t%(c*10))/c == 9 ? t - 9*c : t+c; // calculating higher coordinate, preventing carry over
                if (v[a] == 0) { // 1. only do stuff for unvisited nodes
					v[a] = nextLen; 
					q.add(a); 
				}
                a = (t%(c*10))/c == 0 ? t + 9*c : t-c;  // calculating lower coordinate, preventing carry over
                if (v[a] == 0) { // 1. only do stuff for unvisited nodes
					v[a] = nextLen; 
					q.add(a); 
				}
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```

